In an interesting move by Sony they have developed the technology within their game to restrict item usage even further on a level by level basis.  What this means is that items will work proportionaly with a level up to the Recommended Level of the Item.<br>
<br>
[removed picture of Venomous Axe]<br>
<br>
Notice that the damage is 7(11).  Prior to the last patch it was simply 11.  This means that the weapon is currently a 7/24 not an 11/24.  It can go as low as a 2/24 when wielded by a Level 1.<br>
<br>
The Recommended Level is 35 on this item, so people looking to purchase the item will at least know what Level they need to be to use it properly.  But this is a change from the old usage of the Recommended Level information.  Here is an excerpt for the January patch message:<br>
<br>
Added 'Recommended Level' equal to the current item use level for the several items. All of these items require the player to be level 51+ to equip them and/or use their effects. Setting the 'Recommended Level' field like this just lets the player know what level they need to be to use the item. The actual utility of the item was not affected in any way, this change is purely informational.<br>
<br>
But this obviously isn't the case anymore, despite no posting anywhere in any patch message.<br>
<br>
So what does this mean to the average player?  Well it means that Recommended Level's can now be used to limit the effectiveness of an item even more than just an on/off switch like in the old days.  It really only impacts on the twink market (the outfitting of lower level players with higher level gear), but this is a huge part of the current EverQuest economy.  <br>
<br>
Rumors from Test are also coming through that as of the next patch Fungi Tunic's are being altered in the near future so that the regenerative abilities do not work on characters below Level 50 (and no they aren't kidding this time apparently). On Test it is currently not a retroactive change.<br>
<br>
The real question is: Are these current item changes just an experiment, or will we be seeing an en-masse change to high level gear in the coming months to restrict twinking and the twink economy? If so, will we see more high level gear become tradable instead of no-drop to balance the dint in the economy it will otherwise cause?<br>
<br>
